@politicgame @bravesjt I think Georgia's fairly well covered, testing-wise. You've got to have several symptoms and/or exposure to someone who tested positive. 

They're not testing asymptomatic people yet. We need to get to that point. But symptomatic testing isn't that hard to get here.

COVID-19 is such a weird illness. My daughter also tested positive (She's doing well). 

Neither of us have had a fever or a cough at any point. 

We have had muscle pain, a little shortness of breath at times. She's had nausea, though I haven't. 

Such a wide range of symptoms.

Just found out I have tested positive for COVID-19. 

I've been very blessed ... symptoms thus far have been pretty mild. I'm praying that remains the case. And I continue to pray for those who are having a much different experience with this illness. Wildly unpredictable.

@politicgame @bravesjt I think Georgia's fairly well covered, testing-wise. You've got to have several symptoms and/or exposure to someone who tested positive. 

They're not testing asymptomatic people yet. We need to get to that point. But symptomatic testing isn't that hard to get here.

New antibody tests out of LA and NY suggest that we have a *LOT* of asymptomatic carriers of this virus. 

Don't assume you're healthy or that people around you are. You just can't tell with this thing. And you might be just fine, but the person you pass it to could die.

If we learn that we have more asymptomatic cases that we do symptomatic cases, it won't surprise me. 

You can very easily have this virus and not know it. It hitchhikes unlike anything else I've ever seen.

While I love talking baseball, my day job is  hard/headline news reporter. My life has revolved around COVID-19 for months, even before testing positive. 

I'll say again, I think you'll be shocked in the months ahead when we learn how many asymptomatic cases we have.

I have been extremely careful in public when I've had to go out ... social distancing, N95 mask, gloves/sanitizer, etc. 

This virus is CRAZY contagious. I think if we knew the real number of mild or asymptomatic cases in the country (and the world) it would shock us.
